segment.source: Use the MDT database to stage Windows 10 deployment information (Windows 10)
segment.target: Use the MDT database to stage Windows 10 deployment information (Windows 10)

segment.source: This topic is designed to teach you how to use the MDT database to pre-stage information on your Windows 10 deployment in a Microsoft SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express database, rather than include the information in a text file (CustomSettings.ini).
segment.target: This topic is designed to teach you how to use the MDT database to pre-stage information on your Windows 10 deployment in a Microsoft SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express database, rather than include the information in a text file (CustomSettings.ini).

segment.source: Use the MDT database to stage Windows 10 deployment information
segment.target: Use the MDT database to stage Windows 10 deployment information

segment.source: This topic is designed to teach you how to use the MDT database to pre-stage information on your Windows 10 deployment in a Microsoft SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express database, rather than include the information in a text file (CustomSettings.ini).
segment.target: This topic is designed to teach you how to use the MDT database to pre-stage information on your Windows 10 deployment in a Microsoft SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express database, rather than include the information in a text file (CustomSettings.ini).

segment.source: You can use this process, for example, to add the client machines you want to deploy, specify their computer names and IP addresses, indicate applications to be deployed, and determine many additional settings for the machines.
segment.target: You can use this process, for example, to add the client machines you want to deploy, specify their computer names and IP addresses, indicate applications to be deployed, and determine many additional settings for the machines.

segment.source: Database prerequisites
segment.target: Database prerequisites

segment.source: MDT can use either SQL Server Express or full SQL Server, but since the deployment database isn't big, even in large enterprise environments, we recommend using the free SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express database in your environment.
segment.target: MDT can use either SQL Server Express or full SQL Server, but since the deployment database isn't big, even in large enterprise environments, we recommend using the free SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express database in your environment.

segment.source: Note
segment.target: Note

segment.source: Be sure to enable Named Pipes when configuring the SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express database.
segment.target: Be sure to enable Named Pipes when configuring the SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express database.

segment.source: Although it is a legacy protocol, Named Pipes has proven to work well when connecting from Windows Preinstallation Environment (Windows PE) to the SQL Server database.
segment.target: Although it is a legacy protocol, Named Pipes has proven to work well when connecting from Windows Preinstallation Environment (Windows PE) to the SQL Server database.

segment.source: Create the deployment database
segment.target: Create the deployment database

segment.source: The MDT database is by default created and managed from the Deployment Workbench.
segment.target: The MDT database is by default created and managed from the Deployment Workbench.

segment.source: In these steps, we assume you have installed SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express on MDT01.
segment.target: In these steps, we assume you have installed SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express on MDT01.

segment.source: Note
segment.target: Note

segment.source: Since SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express runs by default on a separate instance (SQLEXPRESS), the SQL Server Browser service must be running, and the firewall configured to allow traffic to it.
segment.target: Since SQL Server 2012 SP1 Express runs by default on a separate instance (SQLEXPRESS), the SQL Server Browser service must be running, and the firewall configured to allow traffic to it.

segment.source: Port 1433 TCP and port 1434 UDP need to be opened for inbound traffic on MDT01.
segment.target: Port 1433 TCP and port 1434 UDP need to be opened for inbound traffic on MDT01.

segment.source: On MDT01, using Deployment Workbench, expand the MDT Production deployment share, expand Advanced Configuration, right-click Database, and select New Database.
segment.target: On MDT01, using Deployment Workbench, expand the MDT Production deployment share, expand Advanced Configuration, right-click Database, and select New Database.

segment.source: In the New DB Wizard, on the SQL Server Details page, enter the following settings and click Next:
segment.target: In the New DB Wizard, on the SQL Server Details page, enter the following settings and click Next:

segment.source: SQL Server Name: MDT01
segment.target: SQL Server Name: MDT01

segment.source: Instance: SQLEXPRESS
segment.target: Instance: SQLEXPRESS

segment.source: Port: blank
segment.target: Port: blank

segment.source: Network Library: Named Pipes
segment.target: Network Library: Named Pipes

segment.source: On the Database page, select Create a new database; in the Database field, type MDT and click Next.
segment.target: On the Database page, select Create a new database; in the Database field, type MDT and click Next.

segment.source: On the SQL Share page, in the SQL Share field, type Logs$ and click Next.
segment.target: On the SQL Share page, in the SQL Share field, type Logs$ and click Next.

segment.source: Click Next again and then click Finish.
segment.target: Click Next again and then click Finish.

segment.source: Configure database permissions
segment.target: Configure database permissions

segment.source: After creating the database, you need to assign permissions to it.
segment.target: After creating the database, you need to assign permissions to it.

segment.source: In MDT, the account you used to run the deployment is used to access the database.
segment.target: In MDT, the account you used to run the deployment is used to access the database.

segment.source: In this environment, the network access account is MDTBA.
segment.target: In this environment, the network access account is MDTBA.

segment.source: On MDT01, start SQL Server Management Studio.
segment.target: On MDT01, start SQL Server Management Studio.

segment.source: In the Connect to Server dialog box, in the Server name list, select MDT01SQLEXPRESS and click Connect.
segment.target: In the Connect to Server dialog box, in the Server name list, select MDT01SQLEXPRESS and click Connect.

segment.source: In the Object Explorer pane, expand the top-level Security node, right-click Logins, and select New Login.
segment.target: In the Object Explorer pane, expand the top-level Security node, right-click Logins, and select New Login.

segment.source: On the Login - New page, next to the Login name field, click Search, and search for CONTOSOMDTBA.
segment.target: On the Login - New page, next to the Login name field, click Search, and search for CONTOSOMDTBA.

segment.source: Then in the left pane, select User Mapping.
segment.target: Then in the left pane, select User Mapping.

segment.source: Select the MDT database, and assign the following roles:
